{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chart-page-js","path":"/isopleth-map","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>shows the data as a third dimension on a map by using lines that connect all points having the same value of some measurable quantity. These lines are called <em>isopleths</em> or <em>isolines</em>.</p>\n<!--more-->\n<p>Isopleth maps are common for showing surface elevations, amounts of precipitation, atmospheric pressure, air temperature, and other measurements that can be shown as a third dimension. </p>\n<p>The isopleth interval is the difference in value between two adjacent isopleths. The values of the isopleths on the map are always multiples of the interval. </p>\n<p>Isopleths never cross or divide. They always form enclosed circles unless a circle extends outside the mapped area. </p>\n<p>A distinction is sometimes made between isometric and isoplethic mapping: isometric maps show real values such as snowfall amounts and isoplethic maps display calculated values such as population density.</p>\n<p>The first use of isolines came from English astronomer Edmund Halley (of the eponymous comet) who in 1686 published the first meteorological a map showing the prevailing maritime winds both in and near the tropics. More importantly, this became widely recognized as the first weather map, well ahead of its time as weather maps did not become common until the early 18th century.</p>\n<h2 id=\"further-reading\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#further-reading\" aria-label=\"further reading permalink\" class=\"anchorLink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Further reading</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Contour_line\">Contour line</a> article on Wikipedia.</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thematic_map#Isarithmic_or_isoline\">Isarithmic or isoline</a> section of <em>thematic map</em> article on Wikipedia.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"references\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#references\" aria-label=\"references permalink\" class=\"anchorLink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>References</h2>\n<p><sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup>. Norman, J., and W. Thrower. <a href=\"https://www.jstor.org/stable/2561832?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents\">\"Edmond Halley as a Thematic Geo-Cartographer.\"</a> <em>Annals of the Association of American Geographers</em> 59 (1969).</p>","excerpt":"shows the data as a third dimension on a map by using lines that connect all points having the same value of some measurable quantity. These…","overview":"<p>shows the data as a third dimension on a map by using lines that connect all points having the same value of some measurable quantity. These…</p>","fields":{"variationOf":null},"frontmatter":{"title":"isopleth map","synonyms":["isoline map","contour line map"],"functions":["geospatial data"],"visualizationTechniques":[{"techniqueId":"MAP","informationType":"spatial location","axisDirection":null}],"informationTypes":null,"axisDirections":null,"examples":[{"title":"Top